Fragile X syndrome

  • Long face, large ears, intellectual disability
  • Predominantly affects intellectual and behavioral functioning.
  • Females less affected due to presence of second X chromosome.

Alport syndrome

  • Sezary syndrome is an erythrodermic cutaneous T-cell lymphoma with a leukemic component.

⭐Guillain barre

  • Sensory symptoms are common but it's not sensory loss.
  • IVIG and plasmapheresis are equally effective.
  • Immune mediated polyneuropathy
  • Nerves show lymphocytic infiltrate

The pathophysiology of GBS involves an inflammatory response against either the myelin or the axon of peripheral nerves due to molecular mimicry and cross reactivity with the infectious antigen.
It's associated with Anti GQ1B antibodies.

Pseudomonas
Pseudomonas species normally inhabit soil, water, and vegetation and can be isolated from the skin, throat, and stool of healthy persons. They often colonize hospital food, sinks, taps, mops, and respiratory equipment. Spread is from patient to patient via contact with fomites or by ingestion of contaminated food and water.

  • Produces extensive necrosis with parenchymal abscesses

  • Lower lobe predilection

  • Can form abscesses

  • or CAP in people with poor immunity (DM, alcohol, pregnancy)

  • Bulging fissure signs +ve on X-ray due to the large amount of inflammation

  • Typically seen as lobar infiltrate in posterior aspect of right upper lung. Source

  • Can form abscesses

  • Caused by rickettsia : obligate intracellular gram -ve bacteria with varying morphology

Chiggers are also classified as mites.

  • The body louse carries ricketsia in it's gut.
  • Tick bite causes itching and during itching tick faeces are inoculated into the the bite site.
  • Ricketsia enter the blood stream and infect the ⭐endothelium⭐ causing ⭐systemic vasculitis⭐.
  • Vasculitis -> loss of intravascular colloid -> ?cause of hypoalbuminaemia
  • Electrolyte loss is common.
  • Brill-Zinsser disease: recrudescence of typhus months to many years after apparently successful treatment.

Epidemic typhus causes the most severe clinical presentation -> severe epidemic typhus may develop ⭐gangrene, leading to a loss of digits, limbs, or other appendage.
⭐High mortality -> lowest estimate is 20%

  • Immunofluorescense assay (IFA) - ⭐Gold standard but expensive. #immunofluorescence #goldStandard
  • An infection is confirmed by a 4-fold increase in antibody titers between acute and convalescent serum specimens - (serologic testing not useful acutely). IgM appears in 1 week, IgG appears in 2 weeks.
  • Blood PCR isn't very sensitive for murine typhus(Harrison's)

Known antigen is immobilized on a glass slide. Test serum is added over the smear. If specific antibodies are present in the serum, the antigen-antibody complex is formed. The serum is washed off and a secondary antihuman immunoglobulin conjugated to a fluorochrome is added. Upon examination under fluorescence microscope, bacteria will only be visible if they have been bound by the antibodies from the patient’s serum.

  • Doxycycline - inhibits protein synthesis by binding to the 30s ribosomal subunit.
  • Doxycycline is contraindicated in pregnancy -> can affect foetal bone and tooth development. Can use azithromycin.

[!INFO] Cohort study -> RR AND OR

Effect is can be assessed only by calculating the odds ratio

Advantage Disadvantages
Cheap and easy possible to "over match" controls
Good for rare diseases "matching criteria" cannot be analysed as risk factors
Quick -> good for analysing outbreaks DO NOT prove CAUSATION ; only association
Can study multiple exposures cannot generate incidence data
Subject to bias
Can only show correlation, NOT causation
Because one can't say which came first - the exposure or the disease
Matching controls will mitigate the effects of confounders.
  • Power of the study can be increased by enrolling 2 controls per case. (but not more, because of how statistics works)

[!INFO] Case control can only assess Correlation ; cannot assess causation

  • Effect can be assessed by calculating relative risk AND Odds ratio

Disorders of sexual maturation

  • 5-alpha-reductase 2 deficiency
    • Deficiency of the enzyme which converts testosterone to dihydrotestosterone in an individual with XY chromosomes.
    • Causes ambiguous genitalia or underdeveloped male genitalia.
  • Androgen insensitivity syndrome
    • XY individual has partial or incomplete sensitivity to androgens.
    • Underdeveloped male seconday sexual characteristics.
    • Feminization or ambiguous genitalia

Tularemia

  • "rabbit fever'
  • From a rabbit / hare / pika / aquatic rodent bite.
  • Regional suppurative lymphadenopathy + ulcer at the bite site.
  • Streated with stretomycin
